s of literature, Reconciling Nature explores the ambivalence within these texts, demonstrating how they reproduce views of nature as threatened, threatening, and useful. The epilogue examines the environmental ideologies associated with the development and deployment of the first atomic bomb.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aNature in literature. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aLiterature : American Literature. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847680340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438476803423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438476803/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles